body:
I'm proposing a way to implement this... Allow specifying the precedence of a parameter when ambiguity happens. E.g. `[Parameter(Precedence = 1)][switch]$Force, [Parameter(Precedence = 0)][string]$Filter`, then `-F`, if not otherwise resolved, would be `-Force`.

For backward compatibility, `Precedence` should be `System.Nullable<System.Int32>` or `System.Nullable<System.UInt32>`. Resolution step **regarding precedence** (of course full name and aliases should be used to resolve parameters before we come to this step) should be:
1. If no parameter candidate has `Precedence.HasValue`, the resolution fails;
2. Collect all parameter candidates with `Precedence.HasValue` that has the largest `Precedence.Value`, say this is collection `A`;
3. If the size of `A` is 1, the parameter resolves to the only element in `A`;
4. Otherwise, the resolution fails.

This won't break current providers that adds a dynamic parameter / an alias of a dynamic parameter `-F`, and is consistent in all providers -- You don't lose `-F` as an alias for `-Force` magically because you are not using built-in providers, you lose it because `-F` resolves before it reaches `-Force` and `-Filter`.

@RichardSiddaway: Being able to add aliases to parameters is not unnecessary. I've run into multiple scenarios where I would gladly have added an alias to a parameter if I could; however, adding shorthand aliases seems like the wrong thing to do.

@iSazonov: Creating a proxy function (that must be then kept up to date over time as commands evolve) is a lot of work just to add a parameter alias. I would greatly prefer being able to simply add an alias to a command via .NET or via a PowerShell command. For example:

```
$cmd = Get-Command -Name Select-Object
if ($cmd.Parameters['First'].Aliases -notcontains 'Top') {
    $cmd.Parameters['First'].Aliases.Add('Top')
    if (-not ($cmd.Parameters['First'].Attributes | Where-Object {($aliasAttribute = $_ -as [System.Management.Automation.AliasAttribute]) -and ($aliasAttribute.AliasNames -contains 'Top')})) {
        $aliasAttribute = New-Object -TypeName System.Management.Automation.AliasAttribute -ArgumentList Top
        $cmd.Parameters['First'].Attributes.Add($aliasAttribute)
    }
}
gps | sort WorkingSet64 -desc | select -top 10 # This fails, so the added alias isn't being recognized
```

I'd like to see that actually work since the collections can be updated, but PowerShell must be using cached metadata for the command when the parser resolves the parameters, so maybe all that's missing is an additional call that would update that command in the command cache.
